1️⃣ Strings (Handling Text Data)
Simple Idea

👉 A string is a collection of characters

Real-World Example

Your name:

"Akshay"

It’s not one value — it’s multiple characters:

A  k  s  h  a  y
In C++
string name = "Akshay";
What Happens Internally

Memory looks like:

name[0] → 'A'  
name[1] → 'k'  
name[2] → 's'  
...

👉 String = array of characters

Mental Model (Never Forget)
String = Character Array + Extra Power
Basic Operations
1. Input & Output
string name;
cin >> name;
cout << name;
⚠️ Important Concept (Placement Favorite)
cin >> name;

👉 Stops at space

Input:

Akshay Kumar

Output:

Akshay   ❌
Solution
getline(cin, name);

👉 Takes full line including spaces

2. Length of String
cout << name.length();
3. Access Characters
cout << name[0];  // First character
Why Strings Matter

Most problems involve:

Passwords, names, patterns, parsing
Connection to What You Know

Array:

char arr[] = {'A','k','s','h','a','y'};

👉 String is just simplified version

How to Remember
String = array + easy functions
2️⃣ Pointers (🔥 MOST IMPORTANT FOR INTERVIEWS)
Simple Idea

👉 Pointer = variable that stores address

Real-World Example

Think of:

House → actual data  
Address → location

Pointer stores address, not data

Example
int x = 10;
int* p = &x;
What This Means
Part	Meaning
x	value = 10
&x	address of x
p	stores address
Memory Visualization
x = 10   (stored at address 100)

p = 100  (points to x)
Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)
Pointer = Google Maps location
Variable = actual place
Access Value Using Pointer
cout << *p;

👉 Output = 10

Symbols Meaning
Symbol	Meaning
&	address of
*	value at address
Why Pointers Exist

👉 To work with memory directly

Used in:

arrays
functions
dynamic memory
linked lists
Deep Understanding
int x = 10;
int* p = &x;

Flow:

x stores 10  
p stores address of x  
*p gives value at that address
Common Mistake 🔥
int* p;
cout << *p;  // ❌ crash (random address)

👉 Pointer not initialized

Connection to Arrays
int arr[3] = {10,20,30};

👉 Internally:

arr = address of first element

So:

cout << *(arr + 1);  // 20
Why Interviewers Love Pointers

Because it tests:

memory understanding
deep logic
problem solving
How to Remember Forever
Pointer = address holder
*pointer = value at that address
